div.p: No. 508, unit 258, VPRS 3253 original papers, Public Record Office, Victoria.

p.style: font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt;

div.p: MS written by Ernst Heyne and signed by M. On 26 June 1867, the Legislative Assembly agreed to a motion: 'That there be laid upon the table of the House a return of the names of public institutions in Victoria to which plants and seeds have been furnished from the Botanical Gardens, Melbourne, during the past ten years; the approximate number of plants and quantity of seeds supplied in each case'. The return was laid upon the table on 10 July (Victoria Parliamentary Debates, vol. 4, 1867, pp. 1352, 1470). 1. Return of total number of plants and seeds supplied from the Melbourne Botanic Gardens to public Institutions in Victoria from 1858 to 1867.

div.p:
Return of the names of public Institutions in Victoria to which plants and seeds have been furnished from the Botanic Gardens Melbourne during the last 10 years. Approximate number of plants and seeds supplied in each case.
Some names of places and institutions in this list have idiosyncratic spelling; these are not noted
except
in cases where there is a serious risk of misinterpretation.

div.p: 2, Return of the approximate number of plants and particulars of seeds supplied in each case.

p.style: font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt;

div.p: Instead of furnishing a detailed return from the departmental books I shall endeavour to generalize on the extensive information available from that source.

p.style: font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt;

div.p:
The Total of plants supplied to public Institutions from the botanic Gardens of Melbourne from 1858 until the eight day
eight day above beginning deleted.
of July 1867 amounts to 355 218.
355 218 above 354 607 deleted.
The plants thus supplied were in cases of quickgrowing kinds one year old, in cases of slowness of growth two and occasionally three years old. In rare instances they were under one year. All plants furnished were of sufficient size to be immediately planted out, provided the most ordinary attention was given to shelter, watering, preparation of soil, protection against cattle, goats &c and arrangements were made for timely planting in the season. The plants were of such size as to render transits inexpensive, indeed they were of such age as I adopted for effecting the plantations under my own control.

p.style: font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt;

div.p: Of the 355 218 supplied about one fourth were grown by pot culture. A leading professional gardener, who for many years was acquainted with the Botanic Gardens, though not connected with it, estimates the real average value of the plants distributed from the general nurseries of the gardens at 6d each at the lowest rate and the value of the potgrown plants at from 1/. to 1/6 each. The 306 upgrown plants including many Californian pines for the Parliamentary Reserve were individually of great value as well as the 136 already this year removed from intended permanent positions to the Treasury Reserve. There was never any difficulty to supply any quantity of plants of the ordinary size during the month of May, the time fixed by Governm. Gazette for distribution. The extent of supply has been ruled by special requirements, by ground actually ready and protected for planting and by priority of arrangements for removal of the plants. Cuttings, of which a vast quantity was supplied, are not included in this return, nor the plants and seeds from the gifts of which institutions in other Colonies reciprocally benefitted.

p.style: font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt;

div.p:
The supply for Victoria embraced annually a large number of coniferous plants, either potgrown or otherwise once or twice transplanted. In the year 1860 approximately 40 000 seedlings of the Italian Stonepine, so valuable for its edible Kernel were raised and nearly the same number in 1866. In the year 1861 approximately 10 000 Deodar Cedars were raised and about 500 Wellingtonias, 2000 of the Himalayan Pinus excelsa and 800 of the Californian Pinus insignis, besides amongst important Pines 1300 Cupressus macrocarpa and 300 Cupressus Goveniana from the same country. In the year 1862 were raised 350 Wellingtonias, 500 Pinus ponderosa 900 Pinus insignis, 350 Pin. Nordmanniana 500 Pinus excelsa, 300 pin. picea 900 Cupressus macrocarpa, 500 Cupress. Goveniana, 1150 Cupressus Lawsoniana. In 1863 Wellingtonia about 300, Pinus Canariensis 2000, Pin. insignis 1100, Pinus ponderosa 300, Cupressus macrocarpa 1500, Cupr. Goveniana 500. In 1864 Wellingtonia 400 Cedrus Deodara 200, P. insignis 1300, Cupress. Lawsoniana 800, Cupress. macrocarpa 700, Cupress. Goveniana 1150. In 1865 Araucaria Bidwilli about 2000, Wellingtonia 250, Pinus insignis 1500, Pin. Smithiana 800, Pinus excelsa 3000, Cupress. macrocarpa 900. In 1866, Wellingtonia 670, Cedrus Deodara 800, Pinus Smithiana 600, Pinus insignis 4500 Cupress. macrocarpa 3300, Araucaria excelsa 1300, Araucaria imbricata (from Chili) 1400. The supply of several mediterranean pines (P. pinaster, Pin. Halepensis, Pin. maritima) was vast. Of miscellaneous pines (many select & rare) the quantity was collectively also very large. Of Cork oaks several thousands were raised, 50 of other evergreen oaks. In 1859 7000 tea plants were raised besides seeds provided for the now florishing tea plantation in Brisbane. Last year again several thousand teaplants were raised, of which a majority together with Cork Oaks, West Austral. Mahagony Coffee and Cinchona plants are reserved for an intended plantation in the Yarra ferntree gullies. About 35000 plants were potgrown in each of the last few years, many of them however requiring two years cultivation
many ... cultivation marginal insertion in M's hand.
but the insatiable demand on the nursery annually, long after the time fixed for distribution, rendered the growing up of plants to many years age an impossibility. For the upgrowth of plants each institution was expected to provide local means. From the return are excluded several thousand willows planted recently at the Yarra banks between the City bridge and Richmond; nor are taken into consideration more than
more than inserted by M above about deleted.
20000 trees, chiefly coniferous, planted into permanent positions over an area of nearly 400 acres under my special control. With but very few exceptions the means of raising and rearing this enormous supply of about 400 000 plants were afforded through the friendly relationship of the Director with many men of science and influence abroad or by mere interchanges.

p.style: font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt;

div.p:

of Cinchonas or Peruvian Bark plants more than 10000 are at this moment the property of the Victorian Government by the means indicated. Some of these plants are in the third year of their growth. Many of the more important plants distributed did either not previously exist in Victoria or were for the first time extensively available in the Melbourne botanic Gardens. The seeds here locally distributed comprised mainly those of the hardier kinds of shrubs & trees, while those of the merely curious or of more tender species were as a general rule reserved for extensive interchanges with foreign countries. Such seeds were always the result of recent gatherings. Seeds are still largely to be supplied this season and many institutions claim also still plants for this years operations, the Board of Land & Works included.
